## Why ordinary p-values fail when you peek

Suppose your team has just finalised a new feature, and now you want to test it with an AB test. In a first step, you specify the KPIs that you want to move, a minimum detectable/relevant effect size, and a false positive rate for your statistical test (the alpha level). With this at hand, you do a power analysis and find that, in order to reliably detect your MDE of interest, you need to run the experiment for 20 days. You lock your runtime and launch the experiment.

In most tech companies, AB test rollouts are tracked on a daily basis via an experimentation platform that is either built in-house, or provided by a third party such as Eppo, Statsig, or Optimizely. These experimentation platforms show treatment effects and inferential statistics and usually update each morning.

So we launch our experiment, and we can check our results every day. On day one, we find a positive treatment effect on our KPI of interest, with a p-value of 0.15. On day two, the treatment effect is still positive, and the p-value has shrunk further to 0.08. On day three, we finally reach significance. For days 3-8, the treatment effect is continuously positive with a p-value lower than 0.05.

By day three, the team is already discussing whether to ship. Should it act on
the result now, or wait until the planned twenty days are over?

Ordinary A/B-test inference does not support an unplanned decision based on this
interim result. Repeated peeking with a rule that allows early stopping raises
the false positive rate.

Why is this the case? The 5% false positive rate of an ordinary p-value is
calibrated for one prespecified decision. If the team can make several
decisions based on interim results, the chance that at least one of them crosses
the threshold increases.

If twenty daily analyses were independent, the probability of at least one
false positive would be $1 - (1 - 0.05)^{20} \approx 0.64$. Daily analyses of
accumulating data are not independent, so 64% is not the false positive rate of
the actual monitoring policy. The dependence between looks does not, however,
preserve the original 5% guarantee. Scenario 1 simulates these correlated daily
looks and measures the resulting false positive rate. For the ordinary
fixed-sample test, the 5% guarantee applies to the single analysis planned for
the end of the experiment.

::: {.callout}
The problem is not opening the dashboard every day. It arises when the interim
results can change whether the experiment continues.
:::

To make valid decisions while the experiment is running, we need inference
designed for repeated looks. This is the purpose of **anytime-valid inference**.

## What SAVI changes

Safe anytime-valid inference (SAVI) lets the team check an experiment and make
decisions as often as needed. In the large randomized experiments considered
here, a 5% SAVI test keeps the false positive rate at 5% or less under repeated
monitoring. The number and timing of the checks do not have to be chosen before
launch. The team can ship early when the data support a positive effect or roll
back when they support harm.

SAVI confidence sequences are generally wider than ordinary fixed-sample
confidence intervals at the same sample size. SAVI is useful when flexible
timing matters enough to accept that loss in precision.

The five scenarios cover different decisions. The first two use the same
twenty-day A/B test to compare daily monitoring when the treatment has no
effect and when it has a large positive effect. The next three use confidence
sequences to certify a backend migration, report a long-term holdout, and
monitor an hourly canary release.

PyFixest implements the linear-regression method of [Lindon et al.
(2026)](https://doi.org/10.1080/01621459.2026.2692052). After the five
operational examples, a final simulation uses this regression formulation to
compare adjusted and unadjusted confidence sequences.^[The closed-form formulas
also make the method fast to compute.]

