An ordinary analysis performed only on day twenty rejects
5\.2% of the time, close to the intended 5%.
Checking the ordinary p-value daily and stopping at the first rejection raises
the rate to 25%. This is below the 64%
back-of-the-envelope number from the introduction, because twenty looks at the
same accumulating data are far from independent. It is nevertheless several
times the specified 5%. SAVI rejects
1\.0% of the same null experiments.

The SAVI rate in this simulation need not equal 5%. The guarantee covers the
full monitoring path, including looks after day twenty, so rejection by the
planned end can be conservative.

False alarms are one problem. The effect sizes selected by naive peeking are
another. The next plot records, for each of the
500 A/A experiments, the estimated effect on the day the
test first rejects:

::: {#7cc1c17c .cell execution_count=6}
``` {.python .cell-code code-fold="true" code-summary="Show the simulation code"}
naive_stop = _stop_day(mirage["regular_p"])
savi_aa_stop = _stop_day(mirage["savi_p"])


def _estimate_at_stop(stop):
    idx = np.where(stop > 0)[0]
    return np.array([mirage["estimate"][i, stop[i] - 1] for i in idx]) * 100


naive_at_stop = _estimate_at_stop(naive_stop)
savi_at_stop = _estimate_at_stop(savi_aa_stop)

naive_fire_rate = (naive_stop > 0).mean()
savi_fire_rate = (savi_aa_stop > 0).mean()
naive_mean_abs = np.abs(naive_at_stop).mean()
