The daily-peeking rule rejects in 25% of these
zero-effect experiments. The reported effects average
3\.9 pp in magnitude. There is a hole around zero
because only extreme early estimates cross the boundary. This is the winner's
curse in the null case: the stopping rule selects effects that look large even
though the truth is zero. The SAVI rule rejects in
1\.0% of the same experiments.

## Scenario 2: effect size and stopping time

The main A/B test is sized for about 80% power to detect a 2 percentage point
lift after twenty days. In this scenario, the treatment raises conversion from
10% to 14%, a 4 percentage point lift. Large effects offer the greatest
opportunity to stop early. The displayed run is representative: among the
simulations that stop within twenty days, its SAVI stopping day is closest to
the median.

The MDE is an input to the power calculation, not a forecast of the true
effect. When the true effect is larger than the MDE, evidence tends to
accumulate faster and SAVI often stops before day twenty. Near the MDE, many
experiments need data after day twenty because the sequential decision boundary
is stricter than the fixed-sample boundary. Smaller effects generally take
longer and may never produce enough evidence to declare a positive effect.
Sampling noise still means that any one experiment can stop earlier or later
than this pattern suggests.

The top panel shows the estimated lift. The ordinary 95% confidence interval is
calibrated for one planned analysis; the 95% confidence sequence covers the
full monitoring path. The bottom panel puts both p-values on the same
$-\log_{10}(p)$ scale.

