At day twenty, the fixed-horizon test detects the effect in
80% of experiments. SAVI has stopped in
16% by day ten and
49% by day twenty. Because SAVI
remains valid after the planned endpoint, the experiment can continue. At the
2 percentage point planning effect,
51% of SAVI runs still need more
data on day twenty. By day forty, SAVI has stopped in
86% of experiments. Among experiments that
stop by then, the median stopping day is 19.

When the true effect is larger than the MDE, SAVI often reaches a valid
decision before the planned endpoint, as in the 4 percentage point example.
When the true effect is equal to the MDE, many experiments run past that
endpoint. Smaller effects generally push stopping times farther out and may
never produce enough evidence to reject the null. SAVI makes the stopping time
flexible; it does not make the planning effect easier to detect.

## Scenario 3: rule out effects larger than a tolerance

A checkout service is moved to a new backend. The change should not affect
conversion, and the product decision allows a difference of at most one
percentage point in either direction. That ±1 pp tolerance matters more than
whether the effect is exactly zero.

The A/A-style test sends 2,000 users per arm per day to the old and new
backends. It stops once the confidence sequence fits inside the ±1 pp
tolerance. The displayed run has the median certification day among one hundred
simulations that certify within the thirty-day monitoring window.

