By week 52, the ordinary interval has missed the true lift at least once in
29% of the simulated holdouts. The
confidence sequence contained the true lift at every review in
100% of the holdouts, in line with its
time-uniform 95% guarantee. With continued monitoring, the probability that an
ordinary interval misses at least once continues to rise.

The simulation makes two simplifying assumptions. First, the true lift remains
constant for a year. Real holdout effects may drift as novelty fades or
features compound. In that case, the treatment coefficient estimates a running
average of the effect rather than the effect in a given week. Second, the
simulation adds new users each week. In a real holdout, the same users may
remain in their assigned group for the full year, so repeated observations from
one user are dependent. Aggregate to one observation per user, or use inference
that accounts for this dependence, before applying the method described here.
See [What the guarantee assumes](#what-the-guarantee-assumes).

## Scenario 5: monitor a canary release each hour

The simulated canary lowers conversion from 10% to 7%, with 500 users per arm
arriving every hour. Before launch, the team specifies the largest acceptable
loss in conversion. Here that tolerance is 1 pp, so the decision boundary is
-1 pp. At each hourly review:

- **Roll back** when the confidence sequence lies entirely below -1 pp. The
  data now support harm larger than the tolerance.
- **Promote** when the confidence sequence lies entirely above -1 pp. Any harm
  still compatible with the data is within the tolerance.
- **Keep watching** while the sequence straddles -1 pp.

Both decisions use the same boundary, so the rules cannot conflict.

::: {#2934976e .cell execution_count=18}
``` {.python .cell-code code-fold="true" code-summary="Show the simulation code"}
CANARY_USERS_PER_HOUR = 500
CANARY_MAX_HOURS = 48
CANARY_HARM_TOLERANCE = 0.01
CANARY_MIXTURE_PRECISION = pf.optimal_mixture_precision(
    nobs=2 * CANARY_USERS_PER_HOUR * CANARY_MAX_HOURS,
    number_of_coefficients=2,
    alpha=ALPHA,
)

canary_full = _experiment_path(
    p_control=0.10,
    p_treatment=0.07,
    seed=8,
    with_intervals=True,
    n_days=CANARY_MAX_HOURS,
    users_per_day=CANARY_USERS_PER_HOUR,
    mixture_precision=CANARY_MIXTURE_PRECISION,
).set_index("day", drop=False)

rollback_hour = int(
    canary_full.loc[
        canary_full["cs_upper"] < -CANARY_HARM_TOLERANCE,
        "day",
    ].iloc[0]
)
rollback_cs = (
    f"[{canary_full.loc[rollback_hour, 'cs_lower']:.1%}, "
    f"{canary_full.loc[rollback_hour, 'cs_upper']:.1%}]"
)
hours_saved = CANARY_MAX_HOURS - rollback_hour
canary_path = canary_full.loc[canary_full["day"] <= rollback_hour]
